answers.body_markdown:
Java&#39;s _instance_ methods are __strictly__ dynamic dispatch.

Any method invocation is _always_ going to hit the &#39;most specific&#39; version of that method based on what the _actual type_ of the `this` reference would be.

The only exception is `super.x()` which will invoke your super, but it&#39;s a one-off transfer. Any invokes done in that method do the dynamic dispatch thing same as usual.

So:

`new B().m1()` invokes B&#39;s `m1()` method, naturally: Because the actual instance&#39;s real type is, naturally, `B`.

That method will invoke A&#39;s `m1()`. A1&#39;s `m1()` code is:

```java
return m3();
```

Which is of course, short for:

```java
return this.m3();
```

and `this` here is __still an instance of `B`__. Hence, dynamic dispatch is applied and it&#39;ll be the `m3()` impl from `class B` that is invoked, thus, `4` is returned.

There is no way to avoid this short of rewriting all those methods.

2 important notes to consider:

* `static` methods don&#39;t do any of this stuff.
* In java, a method&#39;s name includes the parameter types (without generics, i.e. erased) _and_ the return type. So, if you have:

```
class Parent {
  void foo(Object o) {}
}

class Child extends Parent {
  void foo(String o) {}
}

...

Parent p = new Child();
p.foo(&quot;hello!&quot;);
```

Will still invoke Parent&#39;s `foo`, not child&#39;s `foo`, because they are __not the same method__. This is why you always use `@Override` when you intend to override; this means you get a compiler error when you don&#39;t actually end up overriding because the types don&#39;t match.

